        "section_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0012",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#bodies-of-pure-lists"
      }
    ],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "images: list[Image]",
        "section_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0012",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#bodies-of-pure-lists"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0013": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0013",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Editor support everywhere",
    "anchor_id": "editor-support-everywhere",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#editor-support-everywhere",
    "section_text": "And you get editor support everywhere.\n\nEven for items inside of lists:\n\nYou couldn't get this kind of editor support if you were working directly with dict instead of Pydantic models.\n\nBut you don't have to worry about them either, incoming dicts are converted automatically and your output is converted automatically to JSON too.",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "dict"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0014": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0014",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Bodies of arbitrary dicts",
    "anchor_id": "bodies-of-arbitrary-dicts",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#bodies-of-arbitrary-dicts",
    "section_text": "You can also declare a body as a dict with keys of some type and values of some other type.\n\nThis way, you don't have to know beforehand what the valid field/attribute names are (as would be the case with Pydantic models).\n\nThis would be useful if you want to receive keys that you don't already know.\n\nAnother useful case is when you want to have keys of another type (e.g., int ).\n\nThat's what we are going to see here.\n\nIn this case, you would accept any dict as long as it has int keys with float values:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "dict",
      "int",
      "float"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
        "path": "../../docs_src/body_nested_models/tutorial009_py310.py",
        "highlight_lines": [
          7
        ],
        "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/body_nested_models/tutorial009_py310.py hl[7] *}",
        "section_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0014",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#bodies-of-arbitrary-dicts"
      }
    ],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0015": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0015",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/body-nested-models::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Recap",
    "anchor_id": "recap",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-nested-models/#recap",
    "section_text": "With FastAPI you have the maximum flexibility provided by Pydantic models, while keeping your code simple, short and elegant.\n\nBut with all the benefits:\n\n- Editor support (completion everywhere!)\n\n- Data conversion (a.k.a. parsing / serialization)\n\n- Data validation\n\n- Schema documentation\n\n- Automatic docs",
    "section_inline_code": [],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  }
